In the last post we learnt how to create a reference to a scalar, an array, and a hash. In this post, we will learn how to dereference these references and some of the caveats that perl has when it comes to dealing with references. Firstly in Perl it's important to understand that references are scalar values. This means that you can create a reference to a reference, and a reference to a reference to a reference, and so on. This is called a "deep reference" in programming. To declare a reference to any scalar, you use the backslash operator ('\'). For example: my $scalar = 42; my $scalar_ref = \$scalar;
To dereference a scalar reference, you use the dereferencing operator ('$'). For example: my $value = $$scalar_ref; # This will give you the value 42
